Newly elected district councillors Lee Yue-Shun, Tat Cheng, Karrine Fu, Jason Chan, James Pui and Jocelyn Chau (L-R) pose for a photo at the water front in front of the Eastern District Council building in Hong Kong, China, December 17, 2019.  For decades it was known as Little Shanghai, a gritty, waterfront neighbourhood that was the landing spot for many mainland Chinese emigrating to Hong Kong. Densely packed with dilapidated, high-rise apartment blocks looming above bustling neon-lit streets, North Point has long been known as one of the "reddest" â€“ or most pro-Beijing â€“ districts in Hong Kong. During anti-government demonstrations in Hong Kong this year, the district was the scene of street brawls between men in white T-shirts - believed to be pro-Beijing supporters â€“ and black-clad protesters.  But in elections for District Councils in November, a neighbourhood that has long hewed to the pro-Beijing line of Hong Kong's government unexpectedly switched sides. Pro-democracy candidates won four out of five seats in the district, up from one in the last election. In the adjacent Fortress Hill neighborhood, they added another two. REUTERS/Thomas Peter  #hongkong #reuters #reutersphotos

"Hong Kong is similar, the authorities are not thinking about people's wellbeing... I have a fraternal hug for them, and all my solidarity from Chile. Please don't give up."
